06539nam a22007815i 9780812297478DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20202021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122974787 a10.9783/97808122974782doi  a(DE-B1597)563164  a(OCoLC)1223096383  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR508.V45bW45 2021 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a821/.1092231 aWeiskott, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMeter and Modernity in English Verse, 1350-1650 /cEric Weiskott. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNote on Quotations and Scansion -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Modernity: The Problem of a History -- tPART I. ALLITERATIVE METER, TETRAMETER, POLITICAL PROPHECY -- tChapter 1. English Political Prophecy: Coordinates of Form and History -- tChapter 2. The Age of Prophecy -- tChapter 3. The Ireland Prophecy and the Future of Alliterative Verse -- tChapter 4. Tetrameter: The Future of Alliterative Verse -- tChapter 5. Where Have All the Pentameter Prophecies Gone? -- tPART II. ALLITERATIVE METER, PENTAMETER, LANGLAND -- tChapter 6. Alliterative Meter and Blank Verse, 1540–1667 -- tChapter 7. The Rhymelessness of Piers Plowman -- tChapter 8. Langland’s Meter and Blank Verse, 1700–2000 -- tPART III. TETRAMETER, PENTAMETER, CHAUCER -- tChapter 9. Chaucer and the Problem of Modernity -- tChapter 10. Chaucer’s English Metrical Phonology: Tetrameter to Pentameter -- tChapter 11. The Age of Pentameter -- tConclusion. From Archive to Canon -- tAppendix A. English Prophecy Books -- tAppendix B. Some Texts of English Verse Prophecies Not Noted in NIMEV -- tAppendix C. Compilers, Scribes, and Owners of Manuscripts Containing Political Prophecy -- tAppendix D. The Ireland Prophecy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Manuscripts and Rare Printed Books -- tIndex of Anonymous Poems -- tGeneral Index -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat would English literary history look like if the unit of measure were not the political reign but the poetic tradition? The earliest poems in English were written in alliterative verse, the meter of Beowulf. Alliterative meter preceded tetrameter, which first appeared in the twelfth century, and tetrameter in turn preceded pentameter, the five-stress line that would become the dominant English verse form of modernity, though it was invented by Chaucer in the 1380s. While this chronology is accurate, Eric Weiskott argues, the traditional periodization of literature in modern scholarship distorts the meaning of meters as they appeared to early poets and readers.In Meter and Modernity in English Verse, 1350-1650, Weiskott examines the uses and misuses of these three meters as markers of literary time, "medieval" or "modern," though all three were in concurrent use both before and after 1500. In each section of the book, he considers two of the traditions through the prism of a third element: alliterative meter and tetrameter in poems of political prophecy; alliterative meter and pentameter in William Langland's Piers Plowman and early blank verse; and tetrameter and pentameter in Chaucer, his predecessors, and his followers. Reversing the historical perspective in which scholars conventionally view these authors, Weiskott reveals Langland to be metrically precocious and Chaucer metrically nostalgic.More than a history of prosody, Weiskott's book challenges the divide between medieval and modern literature. Rejecting the premise that modernity occurred as a specifiable event, he uses metrical history to renegotiate the trajectories of English literary history and advances a narrative of sociocultural change that runs parallel to metrical change, exploring the relationship between literary practice, social placement, and historical time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEnglish languagexVersification. 0aEnglish literaturexPeriodization. 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish poetryyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aPoeticsxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073921340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812297478423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812297478/original  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-073921-3  University of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-DKUb2020